<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="parabolas-standard-form">
  <title>Standard Form</title>
  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
    <p>
      The curve produced by an equation of form <me>y=ax^2+bx+c, a \ne 0</me>is called an parabola.  An example of a parabola is shown in 
      <xref ref="parabolas-standard-form-figure-1">Figure</xref>. The point at the bottom of the parabola, <m>(2,-3)</m>, is called the vertex of the parabola.  Because the curve could hold water, we refer to it a concave up.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="parabolas-standard-form-figure-1">
      <caption><m>y=x^2-4x+1</m></caption>
      <image>
        <description>
          The graph of the parabola with equation <m>y=x^2-4x+1</m>.  The general appearance is that of a narrow smiley face - this shape is referred to as concave up.  The lowest point on the curve, called the vertex, is <m>(2,-3)</m>.  The curve is symmetric across the vertical line <m>x=2</m>.  This symmetry is illustrate by the fact that the curve passes through the following pairs of point: <m>(1,-2)</m> and <m>(3,-2)</m>, <m>(0,1)</m> and <m>(4,1)</m>, <m>(-1,6)</m> and <m>(5,6)</m>.
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-1.14:5.14] {(x-2)^2-3};                              
              \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-3)} node[below] {(2,-3)};  
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </sidebyside>
  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      Another parabola is shown in <xref ref="parabolas-standard-form-figure-2">Figure</xref>. This time, the point at the top of the parabola, <m>(-2,4)</m>, is the vertex of the parabola.  Because the curve could not hold water, we refer to it a concave down.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="parabolas-standard-form-figure-2">
      <caption><m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x^2-2x+2</m></caption>
      <image>
        <description>
          The graph of the parabola with equation <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x^2-2x+2</m>.  The general is that of a narrow frowny face - this shape is referred to as concave down.  The topmost point on the curve, called the vertex, is <m>(-2,4)</m>.  The curve is symmetric across the vertical line <m>x=-2</m>.  This symmetry is illustrated by the fact that the curve passes through the following pairs of points: <m>(-4,2)</m> and <m>(0,2)</m>, <m>(-6,-4)</m> and <m>(2,-4)</m>.
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-6.67:2.67] {-0.5*(x+2)^2+4};                              
              \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,4)} node[above] {(-2,4)};  
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </sidebyside>
  <p>
    When <m>a \gt 0</m>, the bottom most point on the parabola is the vertex and the parabola is concave up.
  </p>
  <p>
    When <m>a \lt 0</m>, the top most point on the parabola is the vertex and the parabola is concave down.
  </p>
  <p>
    Regardless of the value of <m>a</m>, the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex can be found using the formula 
    <me>x=-\frac{b}{2a}</me>.  The <m>y</m>-coordinate of the vertex is then found by substituting the <m>x</m>-coordinate for <m>x</m> in the equation <m>y=ax^2+bx+c</m>.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine the concavity and vertex of the parabola with equation <me>y=-x^2+10x+3</me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We can see that <m>a=-1</m> and <m>b=10</m>, so let's go ahead and calculate the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex.
        <md>
          <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{b}{2a}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=-\frac{\highlight{10}}{2 \cdot \highlight{-1}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=5</mrow>
        </md>
        Let's substitute <m>5</m> for <m>x</m> in the given equation to determine the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the vertex.
        <md>
          <mrow>y\amp=-(\highlight{5})^2+10(\highlight{5})+3</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=-25+50+3</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=28</mrow>
        </md>
        So the vertex of the parabola is <m>(5,28)</m>.  Also, because the value of <m>a</m> is negative, we know that the parabola is concave down.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      The vertical line with equation <m>x=1</m> is called the axis of symmetry for the parabola shown in   
      <xref ref="parabolas-standard-form-figure-3">Figure</xref>. If we had a paper version off the graph and folded that graph across the axis of symmetry, the two halves of the parabola relative to the axis of symmetry would lie directly atop one another.  Also, note that as you move away from the axis of symmetry that every pair of points that lie equidistant to the left and right of the axis of symmetry have equal <m>y</m>-coordinates.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="parabolas-standard-form-figure-3">
      <caption><m>y=\frac{1}{2}x^2-x-\frac{9}{2}</m></caption>
      <image>
        <description>
          A graph of the parabola whose equation is <m>y=\frac{1}{2}x^2-x-\frac{9}{2}</m>.  The vertex(lowest point) is <m>(1,-5)</m>.  The axis of symmetry, the vertical line <m>x=1</m> is also graphed.  In order to illustrate the symmetry, there are horizontal line segments drawn between two pairs of points on the parabola to illustrate that the are equidistant from the axis of symmetry and have equal <m>y</m>-coordinates.  One of the indicate pair of points is <m>(-1,-3)</m> and <m>(3,-3)</m>, each of which is two units from the axis of symmetry.  The other pair of points is <m>(-3,3)</m> and <m>(5,-3)</m>, each of which is four units from the axis of symmetry.
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-3.87:5.87] {.5*(x-1)^2-5};                              
              \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,-5)} node[below right] {(1,-5)};                              
              \addplot[soliddot,blue] coordinates {(-1,-3)} node[below left] {(-1,-3)};                              
              \addplot[soliddot,blue] coordinates {(3,-3)} node[below right] {(3,-3)};                              
              \addplot[soliddot,brown] coordinates {(-3,3)} node[above left] {(-3,3)};                              
              \addplot[soliddot,brown] coordinates {(5,3)} node[above left] {(5,3)};  
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-0.98:2.98,color=blue] {-3};
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-2.98:4.98,color=brown] {3};
              \addplot[interval,ultra thick,{Stealth}-{Stealth}] coordinates {(1,-6.8) (1,6.8)};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </sidebyside>
  <p>
    In general, the axis of symmetry for a parabola with equation of form <m>y=ax^2+bx+c</m> is the vertical line with equation 
    <me>x=-\frac{b}{2a}</me>.
    Note that this corresponds to the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex of the parabola.
  </p>
  <p>
    When filling out a table of values for a parabola, we can use the axis of symmetry to our advantage.  Once we determine the vertex and calculate a few points to the right of the vertex, we can use symmetry to infer a few points to the left of the vertex.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consider the parabola with equation <me>y=-x^2-6x-5</me>.  The <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex  is calculated thus.
    <md>
      <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{b}{2a}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=-\frac{-6}{2 \cdot -1}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=-3</mrow>
    </md>
    Note that this implies that the axis of symmetry is the vertical line with equation <m>x=-3</m>.
  </p>       
  <sidebyside widths="67% 27%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      The vertex and three points to the right of the vertex were computed and written into <xref ref="parabolas-standard-form-table-1">Table</xref>.
    </p>
               
    <table xml:id="parabolas-standard-form-table-1">
      <caption>Points from a parabola</caption>
      <tabular>
        <col halign="center" />
        <col halign="center"/>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>
            <line><m>x</m></line>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <line><m>y</m></line>
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
