    <figure xml:id="parabolas-standard-form-figure-4">
      <caption><m>y=-x^2-6x-5</m></caption>
      <image>
        <description>
          A graph of the parabola whose equation is <m>y=x^2-6-5</m>.  The parabola is concave down from the vertex <m>(-3,4)</m>.  The parabola is symmetric across the vertical line <m>x=-3</m>.  The symmetry is illustrated by the following pairs of points on the parabola: <m>(-4,3)</m> and <m>(-2,3)</m>, <m>(-5,0)</m> and <m>(-1,0)</m>, <m>(-6,5)</m> and <m>(0,-5)</m>.
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-6.29:0.296] {-5-6*x-x^2};    
            \end{axis}
