  </sidebyside>
  <p>
    The properties we've investigated about a parabola with an equation of form <m>y=ax^2+bx+c, a \ne 0</m> are summarized below.
    <ul>
      <li>
        We determine the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex using the equation <m>x=-\frac{b}{2a}</m>.  We then substitute <m>x</m> with that value in the equation <m>y=ax^2+bx+c</m> to determine the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the vertex
      </li>
      <li>
        The axis of symmetry for the parabola is the vertical line with equation <m>x=-\frac{b}{2a}</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
        The parabola is concave up (opens upward) when <m>a \gt 0</m> and the parabola is concave down (opens downward) when <m>a \lt 0</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
        If there are <m>x</m>-intercept(s) on the parabola, the <m>x</m>-coordinates of those (or that) point(s) are the real number solutions to the equation <m>ax^2+bx+c=0</m>.  When that equation has no real number solutions, the parabola has no <m>x</m>-intercepts.
      </li>
      <li>
        The <m>y</m>-coordinate of the <m>y</m>-intercept is determined by replacing <m>x</m> with zero in the equation <m>y=ax^2+bx+c</m>.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <example xml:id="parabola-properties">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine and state the vertex, axis of symmetry, concavity, and all intercepts of the parabola with the equation <me>y=-2x^2+16x+40</me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
      We begin by finding the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex.
      <md>
        <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{b}{2a}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=-\frac{16}{2 \cdot -2}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=4</mrow>
      </md>
      We now substitute <m>4</m> for <m>x</m> in the given equation to determine the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the vertex.
      <md>
        <mrow>y\amp=-2(\highlight{4})^2+16(\highlight{4})+40</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=-32+64+40</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=72</mrow>
      </md>
      So the vertex of the parabola is the point <m>(4,72)</m> and the axis of symmetry is <m>x=4</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because the value of <m>a</m>, <m>-2</m>, is negative, we know that the parabola is concave down.
    </p>
    <p>
      To determine the <m>x</m>-coordinate(s) of the <m>x</m>-intercept(s) (if any), we need to determine the real number solutions to the equation <m>-2x^2+16x+40=0</m>.
      <md>
        <mrow>-2x^2+16x+40\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{2}}(-2x^2+16x+40)\amp=\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{2}}0</mrow>
        <mrow>x^2-8x-20\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>(x-10)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow>
      </md>
      <md>
        <mrow>x-10\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{ or }\amp x+2\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>x-10\addright{10}\amp=0\addright{10} \amp\amp\text{ or }\amp x+2\subtractright{2}\amp=0\subtractright{2}</mrow>
        <mrow>x\amp=10 \amp\amp\text{ or }\amp x\amp=-2</mrow>
      </md>
      So the <m>x</m>-intercepts on the parabola are <m>(-2,0)</m> and <m>(10,0)</m>.  Note that the axis of symmetry, <m>x=4</m>, is half-way between these two points, which supports that they are correct.
    </p>
    <p>
      To determine the <m>y</m>-intercept of the parabola, we substitute <m>0</m> for <m>x</m> in the given equation.
      <md>
        <mrow>y\amp=-2(\highlight{0})^2+16(\highlight{0})+40</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=40</mrow>
      </md>
      So the <m>y</m>-intercept is the point <m>(0,40)</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="parabola-no-x-intercepts">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine the <m>x</m>-intercept(s), if any, on the parabola with the equation <me>y=x^2-10x+30</me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We need to solve the equation <me>x^2-10x+30=0</me>.  Because the left-side of the equation does not factor, we will use the quadratic formula to determine the solution.
        <md>
          <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-b \pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{-(-10) \pm\sqrt{(-10)^2-4 \cdot 1 \cdot 30}}{2 \cdot 1}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{10 \pm \sqrt{100 - 120}}{2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{10 \pm \sqrt{-20}}{2}</mrow>
        </md>
        Because <m>\sqrt{-20}</m> is not a real number, the equation <m>x^2-10x+30=0</m> has no real number solutions.  Consequently, the parabola with equation <m>y=x^2-10x+30</m> has no <m>x</m>-intercepts.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

